```suggestion
theorem comap_conGen_of_bijective {M N : Type*} [Mul M] [Mul N] (f : M â†’ N)
```
~~I am surprised you need bijectivity here. I would expect this be true when `f` is not ...~~ Nevermind I am being silly
Can you prove an inequality one way using only injectivity/surjectivity?

Neat idea! I can prove one inequality without either, and then the other inequality requires bijectivity. I've separated out the inequality which doesn't require either as conGen_le_comap; but when I use it for the second half of comap_conGen_of_Bijective, it only unifies when I use "apply", not "exact" --
"show term" produces an "exact" statement that won't work. Do you have any idea what's happening?
That seems... weird. I would investigate but it's time for me to go home for the day. Maybe bring it up on Zulip

Thanks! I think I might've figured it out.

I think it's because of the implicit arguments for the instance of LE on Con
âˆ€ â¦ƒx yâ¦„, c x y â†’ d x y

(which here should be a and b)

Lean won't match them correctly with "exact"; it searches harder with "apply"

If I simply give them to "exact", by using @ to specify the implicit arguments as well, that works too

And even better, if I use a fact about LE to avoid using ext (and thus fussing about with the a and b), everything clicks into place just right

Thanks for pointing out that the two directions should be separate - it makes the code much nicer!

To show hf can be inferred

```suggestion
lemma comapQuotientEquivOfSurj_symm_mk (c : Con M) {f : N â†’* M} (hf) (x : N) :
    (comapQuotientEquivOfSurj c f hf).symm (f x) = x :=
```

That's cool! Will the user still see the type of hf explicitly in mathlib (like directly, not hovering over hf or putting the cursor there and looking at the infoview)? I guess my question is, this seems slick, but is it making the lemma harder to use? It may be because I'm a beginner, but I like to know at-a-glance what hypotheses a lemma or theorem requires when I'm on the leanprover-community site
No, it's producing exactly the same lemma with exactly the same hover etc

```suggestion
      rwa [fa, fb]
```

```suggestion
    (((congrArg (fun a â†¦ conGen rel (f w * f y) a) (H x z))).mpr
```

```suggestion
    (congrArg (fun a â†¦ conGen rel a (f (x * z))) (H w y)).mpr
```
I feel like the proof below can be neater if we first prove it for a `MulEquiv` and then suit the hypotheses here using `MulEquiv.ofBijective`. Let me see if I can cook up something...

Here's how I would use a `MulEquiv`. (Unfortunately I can't figure out how to make this suggestion...)

```lean
@[to_additive]
theorem comap_conGen_equiv {M N : Type*} [Mul M] [Mul N] (f : MulEquiv M N) (rel : N â†’ N â†’ Prop) :
    Con.comap f (map_mul f) (conGen rel) = conGen (fun x y â†¦ rel (f x) (f y)) := by
  apply le_antisymm _ (le_comap_conGen f (map_mul f) rel)
  intro a b h
  simp only [Con.comap_rel] at h
  have H : âˆ€ n1 n2, (conGen rel) n1 n2 â†’ âˆ€ a b, f a = n1 â†’ f b = n2 â†’
      (conGen fun x y â†¦ rel (f x) (f y)) a b := by
    intro n1 n2 h
    induction h with
    | of x y h =>
      intro _ _ fa fb
      apply ConGen.Rel.of
      rw [fa, fb]
      exact h
    | refl x =>
      intro _ _ fc fd
      rw [f.injective (fc.trans fd.symm)]
      exact ConGen.Rel.refl _
    | symm _ h => exact fun a b fs fb â†¦ ConGen.Rel.symm (h b a fb fs)
    | trans _ _ ih ih1 =>
      exact fun a b fa fb â†¦ Exists.casesOn (f.surjective _) fun c' hc' â†¦
      ConGen.Rel.trans (ih a c' fa hc') (ih1 c' b hc' fb)
    | mul _ _ ih ih1 =>
      rename_i w x y z _ _
      intro a b fa fb
      rw [â† f.eq_symm_apply, map_mul] at fa fb
      rw [fa, fb]
      exact ConGen.Rel.mul (ih (f.symm w) (f.symm x) (by simp) (by simp))
        (ih1 (f.symm y) (f.symm z) (by simp) (by simp))
  exact H (f a) (f b) h a b (refl _) (refl _)

@[to_additive]
theorem comap_conGen_of_bijective {M N : Type*} [Mul M] [Mul N] (f : M â†’ N)
    (hf : Function.Bijective f) (H : âˆ€ (x y : M), f (x * y) = f x * f y) (rel : N â†’ N â†’ Prop) :
    Con.comap f H (conGen rel) = conGen (fun x y â†¦ rel (f x) (f y)) :=
  comap_conGen_equiv (MulEquiv.ofBijective (MulHom.mk f H) hf) rel
```

The alternative would be to put the creation of a `MulEquiv` inline in the `mul` case of the induction; I think this is neater since it means less argument reshuffling for users who already have a `MulEquiv`.
oh nice, thanks!
